# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ethernet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Autonegotiation for twisted pair is defined in clause 28 of IEEE 802.3. and was originally an optional component in the Fast Ethernet standard.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] It is backwards compatible with the **normal link pulses** (**NLP**) used by 10BASE-T.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The protocol was significantly extended in the Gigabit Ethernet standard, and is mandatory for 1000BASE-T gigabit Ethernet over twisted pair.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] In the OSI model, autonegotiation resides in the physical layer.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] In 1995, the Fast Ethernet standard was released.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Because this introduced a new speed option for the same wires, it included a means for connected network adapters to negotiate the best possible shared mode of operation.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The autonegotiation protocol included in IEEE 802.3 clause 28 was developed from a patented technology by National Semiconductor known as **NWay**.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The company gave a letter of assurance for anyone to use their system for a one time license fee.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Another company has since bought the rights to that patent.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The first version of the autonegotiation specification, in the 1995 IEEE 802.3u Fast Ethernet standard, was implemented differently by different manufacturers leading to interoperability issues.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] These problems led many network administrators to manually set the speed and duplex mode of each network interface.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] However, the use of manual configurations may lead to duplex mismatches.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] These can be difficult to diagnose because the network is nominally working.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Simple network testing utilities such as ping may report a valid connection.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] However, network performance will be significantly impacted by transmission aborts and subsequent Ethernet frame drops that result from a duplex mismatch.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] When a duplex mismatch is occurring, the side of the connection that is using half-duplex will report late collisions, while the side using full-duplex will report FCS errors.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The autonegotiation specification was improved in the 1998 release of IEEE 802.3.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] This was followed by the release of the IEEE 802.3ab Gigabit Ethernet standard in 1999 which specified mandatory autonegotiation for 1000BASE-T.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Autonegotiation is also mandatory for 1000BASE-TX and 10GBASE-T implementations.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Currently, most network equipment manufacturers recommend using autonegotiation on all access ports and enable it as a factory default setting.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Autonegotiation can be used by devices that are capable of more than one transmission rate, different duplex modes (half duplex and full duplex), and different transmission standards at the same speed (though in practice only one standard at each speed is widely supported).
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] During autonegotiation, each device declares its *technology abilities*, that is, its possible modes of operation.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The best common mode is chosen, with higher speed preferred over lower, and full duplex preferred over half duplex at the same speed.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Parallel detection is used when a device that is capable of autonegotiation is connected to one that is not.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] This happens if a device does not support autonegotiation or autonegotiation is disabled on a device.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] In this condition, the device that is capable of autonegotiation can determine and match speed with the other device.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] This procedure cannot determine duplex capability, so half duplex is always assumed.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Other than speed and duplex mode, autonegotiation is used to communicate the master-slave parameters for gigabit Ethernet.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Upon receipt of the technology abilities of the other device, both devices decide the best possible mode of operation supported by both devices.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Among the modes that are supported by both devices, each device chooses the one that is highest priority.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Autonegotiation is based on pulses similar to those used by 10BASE-T devices to detect the presence of a connection to another device.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] These *link integrity test* (LIT) pulses are sent by Ethernet devices when they are not sending or receiving any frames.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] They are unipolar positive-only electrical pulses of a nominal duration of 100 ns, with a maximum pulse width of 200 ns, generated at a 16 ms time interval with a timing variation tolerance of 8 ms.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] A device detects the failure of a link if neither a frame, nor two of the LIT pulses, is received for 50-150 ms.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] For this scheme to work, devices must send LIT pulses regardless of receiving any.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] In the autonegotiation specification, these pulses are called **normal link pulses** (NLP).
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] NLPs used by autonegotiation are still unipolar, positive-only, and with a nominal duration of 100 ns; but each LIT is replaced by a pulse burst consisting of 17 to 33 pulses sent 125 μs apart.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Each pulse burst is called a **fast link pulse** (FLP) burst.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The time interval between the start of each FLP burst is the same 16 ms as between NLPs.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The FLP burst consists of 17 NLP at a 125 μs time interval with a tolerance of 14 μs.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Between each pair of two consecutive NLPs (i.e. at 62.5 μs after the first NLP of the pulse pair), an additional positive pulse may be present.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The presence of this additional pulse indicates a logical 1, its absence a logical 0.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] As a result, every FLP contains a 16-bit data word.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] This data word is called a *link code word* (LCW).
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The bits of the LCW are numbered from 0 to 15, where bit 0 corresponds to the first possible pulse in time and bit 15 to the last.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Every fast link pulse burst transmits 16 bits of data known as a link code word.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The technology ability field is composed of eight bits.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The link code words are also called *pages*.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The base link code word is therefore called a base page.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The next page bit of the base page is 1 when the device intends to send other pages, which can be used to communicate other abilities.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] These additional pages are sent only if both devices have sent base pages with a next page bit set to 1.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The additional pages are still encoded as link code words (using 17 clock pulses and up to 16-bit pulses).
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The base page is sufficient for devices to advertise which ones among the 10BASE-T, 100BASE-TX and 100BASE-T4 modes they support.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] For gigabit Ethernet, two other pages are required.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] These pages are sent if both devices have sent base pages with a next page bit set to one.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The additional pages are of two kinds: *message pages* and *unformatted pages*.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] These pages are still 16-bit words encoded as pulses in the same way as the base page.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Their first eleven bits are data, while their second-to-last bit indicates whether the page is a message page or an unformatted page.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The last bit of each page indicates the presence of an additional page.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The 1000BASE-T supported modes and master-slave data (which is used to decide which of the two devices acts as the master, and which one acts as the slave) are sent using a single message page, followed by a single unformatted page.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The unformatted page contains a 10-bit word, called a master-slave seed value.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] A duplex mismatch occurs when two connected devices are configured in different duplex modes.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] This may happen, for example, if one is configured for autonegotiation while the other one has a fixed mode of operation that is full duplex (no autonegotiation).
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] In such conditions, the autonegotiation device correctly detects the speed of operation but is unable to correctly detect the duplex mode.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] As a result, it sets the correct speed but assumes half-duplex mode.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] When a device is operating in full duplex while the other one operates in half duplex, the connection works reliably only at a very low throughput.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] A full-duplex device may transmit data while it is receiving.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] However, if the half-duplex device receives data while it is sending, it senses a collision and aborts transmission and then attempts to resend the frame.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The full-duplex device will report frame check sequence (FCS) errors on the aborted transmissions.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Depending on timing, the half-duplex device may sense a late collision, which it will interpret as a hard error rather than a normal consequence of CSMA/CD and may not attempt to resend the frame.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] The full-duplex device does not detect any collision and assumes the frame was received without error.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] This combination of (late) collisions reported at the half-duplex end and FCS errors reported by the full-duplex end are indicators that a duplex mismatch is present.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Applications SN H5-274147; Korean Patent Applications SN 22995/93; Taiwanese Patent Applications SN 83104531.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Due to its nature, single-pair Ethernet has its own, optional variant of Auto-Negotiation.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] It uses differential Manchester encoding (DME) pages to negotiate capabilities in a half-duplex manner.
[src:ethernet/autonegotiation] Two different signaling speeds are used: 10/5/2.5GBASE-T1, 1000BASE-T1, 100BASE-T1, and 10BASE-T1S support high-speed mode (HSM) at 16.667 Mbit/s and optionally low-speed mode (LSM) at 625 kbit/s, while 10BASE-T1L supports LSM and optionally HSM.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] CSMA/CD is a modification of pure carrier-sense multiple access (CSMA).
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] CSMA/CD is used to improve CSMA performance by terminating transmission as soon as a collision is detected, thus shortening the time required before a retry can be attempted.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] With the growing popularity of Ethernet switches in the 1990s, full duplex point-to-point operation became standard in FastEthernet and GigabitEthernet.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Collisions don’t occur in such networks.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Also, IEEE 802.3 deprecated Ethernet repeaters in 2011 in favor of Ethernet switches, making CSMA/CD and half-duplex operation less common and less important.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The following procedure is used to initiate a transmission.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The procedure is complete when the frame is transmitted successfully or a collision is detected during transmission.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Start transmitting and monitor for collision during transmission.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] If so, go to collision detected procedure.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Reset retransmission counters and complete frame transmission.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The following procedure is used to resolve a detected collision.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The procedure is complete when retransmission is initiated or the retransmission is aborted due to numerous collisions.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Was the maximum number of transmission attempts reached?
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Calculate and wait the random backoff period based on number of collisions.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Methods for collision detection are media dependent.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] On a shared, electrical bus such as 10BASE5 or 10BASE2, collisions can be detected by comparing transmitted data with received data or by recognizing a higher than normal signal amplitude on the bus.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] On all other media, a carrier sensed on the receive channel while transmitting triggers a collision event.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Repeaters or hubs detect collisions on their own and propagate jam signals.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The collision recovery procedure can be likened to what happens at a dinner party, where all the guests talk to each other through a common medium (the air).
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Before speaking, each guest politely waits for the current speaker to finish.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] If two guests start speaking at the same time, both stop and wait for short, random periods of time (in Ethernet, this time is measured in microseconds).
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The hope is that by each choosing a random period of time, both guests will not choose the same time to try to speak again, thus avoiding another collision.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The **jam signal** or **jamming signal** is a signal that carries a 32-bit binary pattern sent by a data station to inform the other transmitting stations of the collision and that they must not transmit.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The maximum jam-time is calculated as follows: The maximum allowed diameter of an Ethernet installation is limited to 232 bits.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] This makes a round-trip time of 464 bits.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] As the slot time in Ethernet is 512 bits, the difference between slot time and round-trip-time is 48 bits (6 bytes), which is the maximum *jam-time*.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] This in turn means: A station noting a collision has occurred is sending a 4- to 6-byte-long pattern composed of 16 1-0 bit combinations.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The purpose of this is to ensure that any other node that may currently be receiving a frame will receive the jam signal in place of the correct 32-bit MAC CRC; this causes the other receivers to discard the frame due to a CRC error.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] A **late collision** is a type of collision that happens further into the packet than is allowed for by the protocol standard in question.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] In 10-megabit-per-second shared-medium Ethernet, if a collision error occurs after the first 512 bits of data are transmitted by the transmitting station, a late collision is said to have occurred.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Importantly, late collisions are not re-sent by the NIC, unlike collisions occurring before the first 64 octets; it is left for the upper layers of the protocol stack to determine that there was loss of data.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] As a correctly set up CSMA/CD network link should not have late collisions, the usual possible causes are full-duplex/half-duplex mismatch, exceeded Ethernet cable length limits, or defective hardware such as incorrect cabling, non-compliant number of hubs in the network, or a bad NIC.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] A **local collision** is a collision that occurs at the NIC, as opposed to on the wire.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] A NIC cannot detect local collisions without attempting to send information.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] On UTP cable, a local collision is detected on the local segment only when a station detects a signal on the RX pair at the same time it is sending on the TX pair.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Since the two signals are on different pairs, there is no characteristic change in the signal.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Collisions are only recognized on UTP when the station is operating in half-duplex.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The only functional difference between half and full-duplex operation in this regard is whether or not the transmit and receive pairs are permitted to be used simultaneously.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] A **remote collision**, in CSMA/CD computer networks over half-duplex media (10BASE5 or 10BASE2), is a collision that occurs when a frame shorter than the minimum length is transmitted.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] This frame may cause a collision at the remote end, which cannot be detected by the transmitter, so the frame is not resent on the physical layer.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Due to interference on the medium, its data is corrupted and frame check sequence fails, requiring recovery at a higher layer, if possible.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The **channel capture effect** is a phenomenon where one user of a shared medium "captures" the medium for a significant time.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] During this period (usually 16 frames), other users are denied use of the medium.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] This effect was first seen in networks using CSMA/CD on Ethernet.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Because of this effect, the most data-intense connection dominates the multiple-access wireless channel.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] This happens in Ethernet links because of the way nodes "back off" from the link and attempt to re-access it.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] In the Ethernet protocol, when a communication collision happens (when two users of the medium try to send at the same time), each user waits for a random period of time before re-accessing the link.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] However, a user will wait ("back off") for a random amount of time proportional to the number of times it has successively tried to access the link.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The channel capture effect happens when one user continues to "win" the link.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] For example, user A and user B both try to access a quiet link at the same time.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Since they detect a collision, user A waits for a random time between 0 and 1 time units and so does user B.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Let's say user A chooses a lower back-off time.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] User A then begins to use the link and B allows it to finish sending its frame.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] If user A still has more to send, then user A and user B will cause another data collision.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] A will once again choose a random back-off time between 0 and 1, but user B will choose a back-off time between 0 and 3 – because this is B's second time colliding in a row.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Chances are A will "win" this one again.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] If this continues, A will most likely win all the collision battles, and after 16 collisions (the number of tries before a user backs down for an extended period of time), user A will have "captured" the channel.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The ability of one node to capture the entire medium is decreased as the number of nodes increases.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] This is because, as the number of nodes increases, there is a higher probability that one of the "other" nodes will have a lower back-off time than the capturing node.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The channel capture effect creates a situation where one station is able to transmit while others are continually backing off, thus leading to a situation of short-term unfairness.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Yet, the situation is long-term fair because every station has the opportunity to "capture" the medium once one station is done transmitting.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The efficiency of the channel is increased when one node captures the channel.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] A negative side effect of the capture effect would be the idle time created due to stations backing off.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Once one station is finished transmitting on the medium, large idle times are present because all other stations were continually backing off.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] In some instances, back-off can occur for so long that some stations actually discard packets because maximum attempt limits have been reached.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] CSMA/CD was used in now-obsolete shared-medium Ethernet variants (10BASE5, 10BASE2), and in the early versions of twisted-pair Ethernet, which used repeater hubs.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] Modern Ethernet networks, built with switches and full-duplex connections, no longer need to use CSMA/CD, because each Ethernet segment, or collision domain, is now isolated.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] CSMA/CD is still supported for backwards compatibility and for half-duplex connections.
[src:ethernet/carrier-sense-multiple-access-with-collision-detection] The IEEE 802.3 standard, which defines all Ethernet variants, for historical reasons still bore the title "Carrier sense multiple access with collision detection (CSMA/CD) access method and physical layer specifications" until 802.3-2008, which uses new name "IEEE Standard for Ethernet".
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] In computer networking, an **Ethernet frame** is a data link layer protocol data unit and uses the underlying Ethernet physical layer transport mechanisms.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] In other words, a data unit on an Ethernet link transports an Ethernet frame as its payload.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] An Ethernet frame is preceded by a preamble and start frame delimiter (SFD), which are both part of the Ethernet packet at the physical layer.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Each Ethernet frame starts with an Ethernet header, which contains destination and source MAC addresses as its first two fields.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The middle section of the frame is payload data, including any headers for other protocols (for example, Internet Protocol) carried in the frame.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The frame ends with a frame check sequence (FCS), which is a 32-bit cyclic redundancy check used to detect any in-transit corruption of data.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] A data packet on the wire and the frame as its payload consist of binary data.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Ethernet transmits data with the most-significant octet (byte) first; within each octet, however, the least-significant bit is transmitted first.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The internal structure of an Ethernet frame is specified in IEEE 802.3.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The table below shows the complete Ethernet packet and the frame inside, as transmitted, for the payload size up to the MTU of 1500 octets.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Some implementations of Gigabit Ethernet and other higher-speed variants of Ethernet support larger frames, known as jumbo frames.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The optional 802.1Q tag consumes additional space in the frame.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Field sizes for this option are shown in brackets in the table above.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] IEEE 802.1ad (Q-in-Q) allows for multiple tags in each frame.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] An Ethernet packet starts with a seven-octet (56-bit) preamble and one-octet (8-bit) *start frame delimiter* (SFD).
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The preamble bit values alternate 1 and 0, allowing receivers to synchronize their clock at the bit-level with the transmitter.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The preamble is followed by the SFD, which ends with a 1 instead of 0, to break the bit pattern of the preamble and signal the start of the actual frame.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Physical layer transceiver circuitry (PHY for short) is required to connect the Ethernet MAC to the physical medium.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The connection between a PHY and MAC is independent of the physical medium and uses a bus from the media-independent interface (MII) family (GMII, RGMII, SGMII, XGMII, etc.).
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The SFD is immediately followed by the destination MAC address, which is the first field in an Ethernet frame.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The header features destination and source MAC addresses (each six octets in length), the EtherType field, and, optionally, an IEEE 802.1Q tag or IEEE 802.1ad tag.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The EtherType field is two octets long and it can be used for two different purposes.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Values of 1500 and below mean that it is used to indicate the size of the payload in octets, while values of 1536 and above indicate that it is used as an EtherType, to indicate which protocol is encapsulated in the payload of the frame.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] When used as EtherType, the length of the frame is determined by the location of the interpacket gap and valid frame check sequence (FCS).
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The IEEE 802.1Q tag or IEEE 802.1ad tag, if present, is a four-octet field that indicates virtual LAN (VLAN) membership and IEEE 802.1p priority.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The first two octets of the tag are called the Tag Protocol Identifier (TPID) and double as the EtherType field, indicating that the frame is either 802.1Q or 802.1ad tagged.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Its minimum size is governed by a requirement for a minimum frame transmission of 64 octets (bytes).
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] With header and FCS taken into account, the minimum payload is 42 octets when an 802.1Q tag is present and 46 octets when absent.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] When the actual payload is less than the minimum, padding octets are added accordingly.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] IEEE standards specify a maximum payload of 1500 octets.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Non-standard jumbo frames allow for larger payloads on networks built to support them.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The frame check sequence (FCS) is a four-octet cyclic redundancy check (CRC) that allows detection of corrupted data within the entire frame as received on the receiver side.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] According to the standard, the FCS value is computed as a function of the protected MAC frame fields: source and destination address, length/type field, payload data and padding (that is, all fields except the FCS).
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Per the standard, this computation is done using the left shifting CRC-32 (polynomial = 0x04C11DB7, initial CRC = 0xFFFFFFFF, CRC is post complemented, verify value = 0x38FB2284) algorithm.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The standard states that data is transmitted least significant bit (bit 0) first, while the FCS is transmitted most significant bit (bit 31) first.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The standard states that the receiver should calculate a new FCS as data is received and then compare the received FCS with the FCS the receiver has calculated.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] An alternative is to calculate a CRC on both the received data and the FCS, which will result in a fixed non-zero *verify* value.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] (The result is non-zero because the CRC is post complemented during CRC generation).
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Since the data is received least significant bit first, and to avoid having to buffer octets of data, the receiver typically uses the right shifting CRC-32.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] This makes the *verify* value (sometimes called *magic check*) 0x2144DF1C.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] However, hardware implementation of a logically right shifting CRC may use a left shifting Linear Feedback Shift Register as the basis for calculating the CRC, reversing the bits and resulting in a verify value of 0x38FB2284.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The *end of a frame* is usually indicated by the end-of-data-stream symbol at the physical layer or by loss of the carrier signal; an example is 10BASE-T, where the receiving station detects the end of a transmitted frame by loss of the carrier.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Interpacket gap (IPG) is the idle time between packets.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] After a packet has been sent, transmitters are required to transmit a minimum of 96 bits (12 octets) of idle line state before transmitting the next packet.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The different frame types have different formats and MTU values, but can coexist on the same physical medium.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Differentiation between frame types is possible based on the table on the right.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] In addition, all four Ethernet frame types may optionally contain an IEEE 802.1Q tag to identify what VLAN it belongs to and its priority (quality of service).
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] This encapsulation is defined in the IEEE 802.3ac specification and increases the maximum frame size by 4 octets.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The IEEE 802.1Q tag, if present, is placed between the Source Address and the EtherType or Length fields.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The first two octets of the tag are the Tag Protocol Identifier (TPID) value of 0x8100.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] This is located in the same place as the EtherType/Length field in untagged frames, so an EtherType value of 0x8100 means the frame is tagged, and the true EtherType/Length is located after the Q-tag.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The TPID is followed by two octets containing the Tag Control Information (TCI) (the IEEE 802.1p priority (quality of service) and VLAN id).
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The Q-tag is followed by the rest of the frame, using one of the types described above.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] As this industry-developed standard went through a formal IEEE standardization process, the EtherType field was changed to a (data) length field in the new 802.3 standard.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Since the recipient still needs to know how to interpret the frame, the standard required an IEEE 802.2 header to follow the length and specify the type.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Many years later, the 802.3x-1997 standard, and later versions of the 802.3 standard, formally approved of both types of framing.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Ethernet II framing is the most common in Ethernet local area networks, due to its simplicity and lower overhead.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] In order to allow some frames using Ethernet II framing and some using the original version of 802.3 framing to be used on the same Ethernet segment, EtherType values must be greater than or equal to 1536 (0x0600).
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] That value was chosen because the maximum length of the payload field of an Ethernet 802.3 frame is 1500 octets (0x05DC).
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Thus if the field's value is greater than or equal to 1536, the frame must be an Ethernet II frame, with that field being a type field.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] If it's less than or equal to 1500, it must be an IEEE 802.3 frame, with that field being a length field.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Values between 1500 and 1536, exclusive, are undefined.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] This convention allows software to determine whether a frame is an Ethernet II frame or an IEEE 802.3 frame, allowing the coexistence of both standards on the same physical medium.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Novell's raw 802.3 frame format was based on early IEEE 802.3 work.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Novell used this as a starting point to create the first implementation of its own IPX Network Protocol over Ethernet.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] They did not use any LLC header but started the IPX packet directly after the length field.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Novell NetWare used this frame type by default until the mid-nineties, and since NetWare was then very widespread, while IP was not, at some point in time, most of the world's Ethernet traffic ran over raw 802.3 carrying IPX.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Since NetWare 4.10, NetWare defaults to IEEE 802.2 with LLC (NetWare Frame Type Ethernet_802.2) when using IPX.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Some protocols, such as those designed for the OSI stack, operate directly on top of IEEE 802.2 LLC encapsulation, which provides both connection-oriented and connectionless network services.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] IEEE 802.2 LLC encapsulation is not in widespread use on common networks currently, with the exception of large corporate NetWare installations that have not yet migrated to NetWare over IP.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] In the past, many corporate networks used IEEE 802.2 to support transparent translating bridges between Ethernet and Token Ring or FDDI networks.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] There exists an Internet standard for encapsulating IPv4 traffic in IEEE 802.2 LLC SAP/SNAP frames.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] It is almost never implemented on Ethernet, although it is used on FDDI, Token Ring, IEEE 802.11 (with the exception of the 5.9 GHz band, where it uses EtherType) and other IEEE 802 LANs.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] IPv6 can also be transmitted over Ethernet using IEEE 802.2 LLC SAP/SNAP, but, again, that's almost never used.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] By examining the 802.2 LLC header, it is possible to determine whether it is followed by a SNAP header.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The LLC header includes two eight-bit address fields, called *service access points* (SAPs) in OSI terminology; when both source and destination SAPs are set to the value 0xAA, the LLC header is followed by a SNAP header.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The SNAP header allows EtherType values to be used with all IEEE 802 protocols, as well as supporting private protocol ID spaces.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] In IEEE 802.3x-1997, the IEEE Ethernet standard was changed to explicitly allow the use of the 16-bit field after the MAC addresses to be used as a length field or a type field.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The AppleTalk v2 protocol suite on Ethernet ("EtherTalk") uses IEEE 802.2 LLC + SNAP encapsulation.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] for untagged frames, since the packet size is a maximum 1500 octet payload + 8 octet preamble + 14 octet header + 4 octet trailer + minimum interpacket gap corresponding to 12 octets = 1538 octets.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] where the physical layer net bit rate (the wire bit rate) depends on the Ethernet physical layer standard, and may be 10 Mbit/s, 100 Mbit/s, 1 Gbit/s or 10 Gbit/s.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Maximum throughput for 100BASE-TX Ethernet is consequently 97.53 Mbit/s without 802.1Q, and 97.28 Mbit/s with 802.1Q.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Channel utilization is a concept often confused with protocol efficiency.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] It considers only the use of the channel, disregarding the nature of the data transmitted – either payload or overhead.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] At the physical layer, the link channel and equipment do not know the difference between data and control frames.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The total time considers the round-trip time along the channel, the processing time in the hosts and the time transmitting data and acknowledgements.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] The time spent transmitting data includes data and acknowledgements.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] A runt frame is an Ethernet frame that is less than the IEEE 802.3's minimum length of 64 octets.
[src:ethernet/ethernet-frame] Runt frames are most commonly caused by collisions; other possible causes are a malfunctioning network card, buffer underrun, duplex mismatch or software issues.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet has since been refined to support higher bit rates, a greater number of nodes, and longer link distances, but retains much backward compatibility.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Over time, Ethernet has largely replaced competing wired LAN technologies such as Token Ring, FDDI and ARCNET.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The original 10BASE5 Ethernet uses a thick coaxial cable as a shared medium.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Its immediate successor 10BASE2 uses a thinner and more flexible cable that is both less expensive and easier to use.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] More modern Ethernet variants use twisted pair and fiber optic links in conjunction with switches.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Over the course of its history, Ethernet data transfer rates have been increased from the original 2.94 Mbit/s to the latest 800 Gbit/s, with rates up to 1.6 Tbit/s under development.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The Ethernet standards include several wiring and signaling variants of the OSI physical layer.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Systems communicating over Ethernet divide a stream of data into shorter pieces called frames.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Each frame contains source and destination addresses, and error-checking data so that damaged frames can be detected and discarded; most often, higher-layer protocols trigger retransmission of lost frames.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Per the OSI model, Ethernet provides services up to and including the data link layer.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The 48-bit MAC address was adopted by other IEEE 802 networking standards, including IEEE 802.11 (Wi-Fi), as well as by FDDI.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] EtherType values are also used in Subnetwork Access Protocol (SNAP) headers.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet is widely used in homes and industry, and interworks well with wireless Wi-Fi technologies.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet commonly carries Internet Protocol traffic, and so Ethernet is considered one of the key technologies that make up the Internet.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The original forms of Ethernet used a shared communications channel.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] This concept originated in ALOHAnet, designed in the late 1960s by Norman Abramson.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] ALOHANet was a 4800 bps radio network used by the University of Hawaii.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] When a sender detected that its message hadn't been received, it would resend the message after waiting for a randomly selected period of time.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In 1972, Robert Metcalfe and David Boggs adapted the ALOHAnet approach to transmission over a shared coaxial cable in the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (Xerox PARC).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] This network connected ALTO computers using a coaxial cable.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] It first ran on May 22, 1973 with a bit rate of 2.94 Mbps.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In a memo written at that time, Metcalfe named the concept "Ethernet." The name was inspired by the former idea that the universe was filled with a "luminiferous aether" that carried electromagnetic waves, and calling it Ethernet emphasized its ability to run over any transmission medium.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet improved the original ALOHANet design because a sender would first listen to the channel to determine if it was already in use.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The combination of the new idea of *Carrier Sense* with *Multiple Access* and *Collision Detection* from ALOHANet became Carrier-Sense Multiple Access/Collision Detection, or CSMA/CD.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In 1975, Metcalfe, Boggs and their colleagues Charles Thacker and Butler Lampson filed for a patent on Ethernet, which was granted in 1977.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] By 1976, 100 ALTOs at Xerox PARC were connected using Ethernet.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In July 1976, Metcalfe and Boggs published the seminal paper *Ethernet: Distributed Packet Switching for Local Computer Networks* in Communications of the ACM (CACM).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Subsequently between 1976-1978 Ron Crane, Bob Garner, Hal Murray, and Roy Ogus designed a 10Mbps version of Ethernet running over coaxial cable.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] There were multiple local area network technologies in the 1970s.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] These included IBM's Token Ring, Network Systems Corporation's HYPERchannel and Datapoint's ARCnet.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Version 2 was published in November 1982.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In June 1981, the Institute of Electronic and Electrical Engineers (IEEE) Project 802 (for local area network standards) created an 802.3 subcommittee to produce an Ethernet standard based on DIX.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In 1983, a standard was published for 10 Mbps Ethernet over a coaxial cable of up to 500 meters (10BASE5).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] It differed only in some details from the DIX standard.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] As part of the standardization process, Xerox turned over all its Ethernet patents to the IEEE, and anyone can implement 802.3.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] IEEE 802.3 is now considered the same as Ethernet.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The cooperation of Xerox with Intel and Digital on the Ethernet standard ultimately made it a truly open standard.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In June 1979, Metcalfe left Xerox to found the Computer, Communication, and Compatibility Corporation, better known as 3Com, along with Howard Charney, Ron Crane, Greg Shaw, and Bill Krause.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Metcalfe's vision was to sell Ethernet adapters for all personal computers.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Apple quickly agreed, but IBM was committed to their own LAN protocol, the Token Ring.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Nonetheless, 3Com developed the EtherLink ISA adapter and started shipping it with DOS driver software, making it usable on IBM PCs.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The EtherLink adapter had several advantages over competitors.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] It was the first network interface card (NIC) to use VLSI semiconductor technology (developed in partnership with Seeq Technologies).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] This meant most of the functions, including the transceiver, could be contained on a single chip, so the price for Etherlink ($950) was significantly lower than of its competitors.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] 3Com introduced a new, thinner coaxial cable for the card, called Thin Ethernet, making it more convenient to install and use.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Finally, Etherlink was the first Ethernet adapter for the IBM PC.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Because both businesses and home users adopted the IBM PC, its market expanded rapidly, and by 1982, IBM was shipping 200,000 units a month.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Since IBM hadn't realized that businesses would want the computers connected by a network, Etherlink sales filled the vacuum, and in 1984, 3Com was able to file for a public stock offering.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The Etherlink approach was standardized by IEEE as 10BASE2 in 1984.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Also in the early 1980s, Novell began selling Network Interface Cards (NICs) to go with its NetWare operating system.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] These NE2000 NICs were all Ethernet, and because NetWare became an important application for businesses, this increased the demand for Ethernet adapters.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Then in 1989, Novell sold its NIC business and licensed the NE2000 card, creating a highly competitive market and driving the price of Ethernet cards down, while cards for other technologies, such as IBM's Token Ring, remained high.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Starting in late 1983, AT&T and NCR promoted a star configuration using unshielded twisted pair cabling (UTP), or regular telephone wire.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] This became StarLAN, running at 1Mbps over cables up to 500 meters, and was standardized as 1BASE5 by IEEE 802.3, but on August 17, 1987, SynOptics introduced LATTISNET with 10Mbps Ethernet also over regular telephone wire (UTP).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In the fall of 1990, the IEEE issued the 802.3i standard for 10BASE-T, Ethernet over twisted pairs, and the following year, Ethernet sales nearly doubled.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] By 1992, Ethernet was the de facto standard for LANs.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In the 1990s, the proliferation of PCs combined with their increasing power drove demand for much faster network infrastructure.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The Kalpana EtherSwitch EPS-700 helped to meet this demand by increasing the speed of Ethernet dramatically.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The switch allowed multiple simultaneous data transmission paths and it used faster cut-through bridging technology in place of store-and-forward.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The switch was marketed as a way to improve network performance rather than as a way to connect different LANs, creating a new market category.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Then in 1993, Kalpana introduced full-duplex mode for switches, potentially doubling the data transmission rate.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In 1997, the IEEE standardized full-duplex flow-control switched in 802.3x.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The 10Mbps rate of Ethernet was still too slow for some networks, though, and most larger networks planned to use FDDI, a very expensive alternative to Ethernet.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In August 1991 Howard Charney, David Boggs, Ron Crane, and Larry Birenbaum founded Grand Junction Networks to build and market 100Mbps Ethernet equipment.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Their announcement in 1992 triggered a standards war over whether to maintain backward compatibility with the original Ethernet CSMA/CD standard or to adopt a demand-priority protocol pushed by HP and AT&T.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Since the competing groups were unable to come to an agreement, IEEE set up a new group, 802.12, for the demand-priority scheme.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The supporters of backward compatibility formed the Fast Ethernet Alliance in 1993 to publish an interoperability specification that became the 100BASE-TX standard (also known as Fast Ethernet).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] At the same time, Grand Junction shipped the first Fast Ethernet hubs and NICs, and more companies announced Fast Ethernet equipment.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In 1994, Sun Microsystems, followed by 3Com, DEC, and others, shipped 100BASE-TX compliant products, and the IEEE 802.3u specification for Fast Ethernet was approved.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Since 1999, Ethernet's maximum speed has increased with the introductions of Gigabit Ethernet (802.3ab), 2.5 and 5 Gbit/s Ethernet (802.3bz), 10 Gigabit Ethernet (802.3ae), 25 Gigabit Ethernet (802.3by), 50 Gigabit Ethernet (802.3cd), 100 Gigabit Ethernet (802.3ba), and Terabit Ethernet (802.3df).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In February 1980, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) started project 802 to standardize local area networks (LAN).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The DIX group with Gary Robinson (DEC), Phil Arst (Intel), and Bob Printis (Xerox) submitted the so-called *Blue Book* CSMA/CD specification as a candidate for the LAN specification.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In addition to CSMA/CD, Token Ring (supported by IBM) and Token Bus (selected and henceforward supported by General Motors) were also considered as candidates for a LAN standard.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Competing proposals and broad interest in the initiative led to strong disagreement over which technology to standardize.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In December 1980, the group was split into three subgroups, and standardization proceeded separately for each proposal.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The development of the CSMA/CD standard was slowed by conflict over issues such as baseband versus broadband and the lengths of address fields.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Some members of the DIX group became impatient with the process and concerned that the ultimate CSMA/CD standard would differ significantly from their "Blue Book" de facto standard.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] They turned instead to the European Computer Manufacturers Association (ECMA), where Friedrich Röscheisen of Siemens helped to introduce the Blue Book as a candidate standard to a newly created "Local Networks" Task Group (TC24).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Gary Robinson later claimed to have instigated the effort to convince ECMA to standardize CSMA/CD.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] ECMA approved a standard in June 1982 that was very close to the DIX de facto standard.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Because the DIX proposal was the most technically complete and because of the speedy action taken by ECMA, the IEEE group felt compelled to approve the 802.3 CSMA/CD standard in December 1982.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] It differed only slightly from the DIX standard in terminology and frame format.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] IEEE published the 802.3 standard as a draft in 1983 and as a standard in 1985.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The ISO 8802-3 standard was published on March 23, 1989.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The IEEE has approved changes to its 802.3 (Ethernet) standard regularly since 1985.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The current standard is available from the IEEE website.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] With each change to the standard, the IEEE first issues a supplement with a letter designation added to IEEE 802.3.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] For example, IEEE 802.3u refers to Fast Ethernet.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Then when the supplement is formally approved, it is merged with the main standard.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Subsequent standards have provided for ever-faster versions of Ethernet, additional physical media, and network management.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] For a table of IEEE Ethernet standards, see IEEE 802.3 § Communication standards.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet has evolved to include higher bandwidth, improved medium access control methods, and different physical media.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The multidrop coaxial cable was replaced with physical point-to-point links connected by Ethernet repeaters or switches.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet stations communicate by sending each other data packets: blocks of data individually sent and delivered.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] As with other IEEE 802 LANs, each adapter comes programmed with a globally unique 48-bit MAC address so that each Ethernet station has a unique address.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The MAC addresses are used to specify both the destination and the source of each data packet.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet establishes link-level connections, which can be defined using both the destination and source addresses.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] On reception of a transmission, the receiver uses the destination address to determine whether the transmission is relevant to the station or should be ignored.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] A network interface normally does not accept packets addressed to other Ethernet stations.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] An EtherType field in each frame is used by the operating system on the receiving station to select the appropriate protocol module (e.g., an Internet Protocol version such as IPv4).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet frames are said to be *self-identifying*, because of the EtherType field.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Self-identifying frames make it possible to intermix multiple protocols on the same physical network and allow a single computer to use multiple protocols together.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Despite the evolution of Ethernet technology, all generations of Ethernet (excluding early experimental versions) use the same frame formats.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Mixed-speed networks can be built using Ethernet switches and repeaters supporting the desired Ethernet variants.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Due to the ubiquity of Ethernet and the ever-decreasing cost of the hardware needed to support it, by 2004 most manufacturers built Ethernet interfaces directly into PC motherboards, eliminating the need for a separate network card.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet was originally based on the idea of computers communicating over a shared coaxial cable acting as a broadcast transmission medium.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The method used was similar to those used in radio systems, with the common cable providing the communication channel likened to the *Luminiferous aether* in 19th-century physics, and it was from this reference that the name *Ethernet* was derived.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The original Ethernet's shared coaxial cable (the shared medium) traversed a building or campus to connect every attached machine.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] A scheme known as carrier-sense multiple access with collision detection (CSMA/CD) governed the way the computers shared the channel.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] This scheme was simpler than competing Token Ring or Token Bus technologies.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Computers are connected to an Attachment Unit Interface (AUI) transceiver, which is in turn connected to the cable (with thin Ethernet, the transceiver is usually integrated into the network adapter).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] While a simple passive wire is highly reliable for small networks, it is not reliable for large extended networks, where damage to the wire in a single place, or a single bad connector, can make the whole Ethernet segment unusable.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Through the first half of the 1980s, Ethernet's 10BASE5 implementation utilised a coaxial cable 0.375 inches (9.5 mm) in diameter, later referred to as *thick Ethernet* or *thicknet*.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Its successor, 10BASE2, called *thin Ethernet* or *thinnet*, used the RG-58 coaxial cable.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The emphasis was on making installation of the cable easier and less costly.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Since all communication happens on the same wire, any information sent by one computer is received by all, even if that information is intended for just one destination.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The network interface card interrupts the CPU only when applicable packets are received: the card ignores information not addressed to it.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Use of a single cable also means that the data bandwidth is shared, such that, for example, available data bandwidth to each device is halved when two stations are simultaneously active.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] A collision happens when two stations attempt to transmit at the same time.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] They corrupt transmitted data and require stations to re-transmit.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The loss of data and retransmission reduce throughput.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In the worst case, where multiple active hosts connected with maximum allowed cable length attempt to transmit many short frames, excessive collisions can reduce throughput dramatically.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] However, a Xerox report in 1980, published in Communications of the ACM, studied the performance of an existing Ethernet installation under both normal and artificially generated heavy load.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The report claimed that 98% throughput on the LAN was observed.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] This is in contrast with token passing LANs (Token Ring, Token Bus), all of which suffer throughput degradation as each new node comes into the LAN, due to token waits.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] This report was controversial, as modeling showed that collision-based networks theoretically became unstable under loads as low as 37% of nominal capacity.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Many early researchers failed to understand these results.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Performance on real networks is significantly better.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In a modern Ethernet, the stations do not all share one channel through a shared cable or a simple repeater hub; instead, each station communicates with a switch, which in turn forwards that traffic to the destination station.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In this topology, collisions are only possible if the station and switch attempt to communicate with each other at the same time, and collisions are limited to this link.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Furthermore, the 10BASE-T standard introduced a full duplex mode of operation, which became familiar with Fast Ethernet and the de facto standard with Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In full duplex, a switch and a station can send and receive simultaneously, and therefore modern Ethernet networks are completely collision-free.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] For signal degradation and timing reasons, coaxial Ethernet segments have a restricted size.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Somewhat larger networks can be built by using an Ethernet repeater.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Early repeaters had only two ports, allowing, at most, a doubling of network size.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Once repeaters with more than two ports became available, it was possible to wire the network in a star topology.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Early experiments with star topologies (called *Fibernet*) using optical fiber were published by 1978.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Shared cable Ethernet is always hard to install in offices because its bus topology is in conflict with the star topology cable plans designed into buildings for telephony.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Modifying Ethernet to conform to twisted-pair telephone wiring already installed in commercial buildings provided another opportunity to lower costs, expand the installed base, and leverage building design, and, thus, twisted-pair Ethernet was the next logical development in the mid-1980s.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet on unshielded twisted-pair cables (UTP) began with StarLAN at 1 Mbit/s in the mid-1980s.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In 1987 SynOptics introduced the first twisted-pair Ethernet at 10 Mbit/s in a star-wired cabling topology with a central hub, later called LattisNet.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] These evolved into 10BASE-T, which was designed for point-to-point links only, and all termination was built into the device.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] This changed repeaters from a specialist device used at the center of large networks to a device that every twisted pair-based network with more than two machines had to use.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The tree structure that resulted from this made Ethernet networks easier to maintain by preventing most faults with one peer or its associated cable from affecting other devices on the network.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Every packet is sent to every other port on the repeater, so bandwidth and security problems are not addressed.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The total throughput of the repeater is limited to that of a single link, and all links must operate at the same speed.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] While repeaters can isolate some aspects of Ethernet segments, such as cable breakages, they still forward all traffic to all Ethernet devices.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The entire network is one collision domain, and all hosts have to be able to detect collisions anywhere on the network.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] This limits the number of repeaters between the farthest nodes and creates practical limits on how many machines can communicate on an Ethernet network.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Segments joined by repeaters have to all operate at the same speed, making phased-in upgrades impossible.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] To alleviate these problems, bridging was created to communicate at the data link layer while isolating the physical layer.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] With bridging, only well-formed Ethernet packets are forwarded from one Ethernet segment to another; collisions and packet errors are isolated.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] At initial startup, Ethernet bridges work somewhat like Ethernet repeaters, passing all traffic between segments.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] By observing the source addresses of incoming frames, the bridge then builds an address table associating addresses to segments.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Once an address is learned, the bridge forwards network traffic destined for that address only to the associated segment, improving overall performance.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Broadcast traffic is still forwarded to all network segments.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Bridges also overcome the limits on total segments between two hosts and allow the mixing of speeds, both of which are critical to the incremental deployment of faster Ethernet variants.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In 1989, Motorola Codex introduced their 6310 EtherSpan, and Kalpana introduced their EtherSwitch; these were examples of the first commercial Ethernet switches.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Early switches such as this used cut-through switching where only the header of the incoming packet is examined before it is either dropped or forwarded to another segment.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] One drawback of this method is that it does not readily allow a mixture of different link speeds.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Another is that packets that have been corrupted are still propagated through the network.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The eventual remedy for this was a return to the original store and forward approach of bridging, where the packet is read into a buffer on the switch in its entirety, its frame check sequence verified and only then the packet is forwarded.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In modern network equipment, this process is typically done using application-specific integrated circuits allowing packets to be forwarded at wire speed.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] When a twisted pair or fiber link segment is used, and neither end is connected to a repeater, full-duplex Ethernet becomes possible over that segment.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In full-duplex mode, both devices can transmit and receive to and from each other at the same time, and there is no collision domain.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] This doubles the aggregate bandwidth of the link and is sometimes advertised as double the link speed (for example, 200 Mbit/s for Fast Ethernet).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The elimination of the collision domain for these connections also means that all the link's bandwidth can be used by the two devices on that segment and that segment length is not limited by the constraints of collision detection.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Since packets are typically delivered only to the port they are intended for, traffic on a switched Ethernet is less public than on shared-medium Ethernet.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Despite this, switched Ethernet should still be regarded as an insecure network technology, because it is easy to subvert switched Ethernet systems by means such as ARP spoofing and MAC flooding.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The bandwidth advantages, the improved isolation of devices from each other, the ability to easily mix different speeds of devices and the elimination of the chaining limits inherent in non-switched Ethernet have made switched Ethernet the dominant network technology.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Advanced networking features in switches use Shortest Path Bridging (SPB) or the Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) to maintain a loop-free, meshed network, allowing physical loops for redundancy (STP) or load-balancing (SPB).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Shortest Path Bridging includes the use of the link-state routing protocol IS-IS to allow larger networks with shortest path routes between devices.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In 2016, Ethernet replaced InfiniBand as the most popular system interconnect of TOP500 supercomputers.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In many industrial systems, Ethernet and fieldbus coexist, each performing certain roles, and data is exchanged between them through gateways.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The Ethernet physical layer evolved over a considerable time span and encompasses coaxial, twisted pair and fiber-optic physical media interfaces, with speeds from 1 Mbit/s to 400 Gbit/s.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The first introduction of twisted-pair CSMA/CD was StarLAN, standardized as 802.3 1BASE5.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] While 1BASE5 had little market penetration, it defined the physical apparatus (wire, plug/jack, pin-out, and wiring plan) that would be carried over to 10BASE-T through 10GBASE-T.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The most common forms used are 10BASE-T, 100BASE-TX, and 1000BASE-T.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] All three use twisted-pair cables and 8P8C modular connectors.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] They run at 10 Mbit/s, 100 Mbit/s, and 1 Gbit/s, respectively.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Fiber optic variants of Ethernet (that commonly use SFP modules) are also very popular in larger networks, offering high performance, better electrical isolation and longer distance (tens of kilometers with some versions).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In general, network protocol stack software will work similarly on all varieties.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] In IEEE 802.3, a datagram is called a packet or frame.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] *Packet* is used to describe the overall transmission unit and includes the preamble, start frame delimiter (SFD) and carrier extension (if present).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The *frame* begins after the start frame delimiter with a frame header featuring source and destination MAC addresses and the EtherType field giving either the protocol type for the payload protocol or the length of the payload.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The middle section of the frame consists of payload data, including any headers for other protocols (for example, Internet Protocol) carried in the frame.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The frame ends with a 32-bit cyclic redundancy check, which is used to detect corruption of data in transit.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Notably, Ethernet packets have no time-to-live field, leading to possible problems in the presence of a switching loop.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Autonegotiation is the procedure by which two connected devices choose common transmission parameters, e.g., speed and duplex mode.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Autonegotiation was initially an optional feature, first introduced with 100BASE-TX (1995 IEEE 802.3u Fast Ethernet standard), and is backward compatible with 10BASE-T.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The specification was improved in the 1998 release of IEEE 802.3.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Autonegotiation is mandatory for 1000BASE-T and faster.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] A switching loop or bridge loop occurs in computer networks when there is more than one Layer 2 (OSI model) path between two endpoints (e.g., multiple connections between two network switches or two ports on the same switch connected to each other).
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The loop creates broadcast storms as broadcasts and multicasts are forwarded by switches out every port, the switch or switches will repeatedly rebroadcast the broadcast messages flooding the network.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Since the Layer 2 header does not support a *time to live* (TTL) value, if a frame is sent into a looped topology, it can loop forever.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] A physical topology that contains switching or bridge loops is attractive for redundancy reasons, yet a switched network must not have loops.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] The solution is to allow physical loops, but create a loop-free logical topology using the SPB protocol or the older STP on the network switches.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] A node that is sending longer than the maximum transmission window for an Ethernet packet is considered to be *jabbering*.
[src:ethernet/ethernet] Depending on the physical topology, jabber detection and remedy differ somewhat.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] In IEEE 802 LAN/MAN standards, the **medium access control** (**MAC**), also called **media access control**, is the layer that controls the hardware responsible for interaction with the wired (electrical or optical) or wireless transmission medium.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] The MAC sublayer and the logical link control (LLC) sublayer together make up the data link layer.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] The LLC provides flow control and multiplexing for the logical link (i.e.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] EtherType, 802.1Q VLAN tag etc), while the MAC provides flow control and multiplexing for the transmission medium.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] These two sublayers together correspond to layer 2 of the OSI model.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] For compatibility reasons, LLC is optional for implementations of IEEE 802.3 (the frames are then "raw"), but compulsory for implementations of other IEEE 802 physical layer standards.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] Within the hierarchy of the OSI model and IEEE 802 standards, the MAC sublayer provides a control abstraction of the physical layer such that the complexities of physical link control are invisible to the LLC and upper layers of the network stack.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] Thus, any LLC sublayer (and higher layers) may be used with any MAC.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] In turn, the medium access control block is formally connected to the PHY via a media-independent interface.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] Although the MAC block is today typically integrated with the PHY within the same device package, historically any MAC could be used with any PHY, independent of the transmission medium.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] For topologies with a collision domain (bus, ring, mesh, point-to-multipoint topologies), the channel access method controls when data is sent and when waiting is necessary to avoid collisions.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] Additionally, the MAC is also responsible for compensating for collisions by initiating retransmission if a jam signal is detected.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] When receiving data from the physical layer, the MAC block ensures data integrity by verifying the sender's frame check sequences and strips off the sender's preamble and padding before passing the data up to the higher layers.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] The local network addresses used in IEEE 802 networks and FDDI networks are called *MAC addresses*; they are based on the addressing scheme that was used in early Ethernet implementations.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] A MAC address is intended as a unique serial number.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] MAC addresses are typically assigned to network interface hardware at the time of manufacture.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] The most significant part of the address identifies the manufacturer, who assigns the remainder of the address, thus providing a potentially unique address.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] This makes it possible for frames to be delivered on a network link that interconnects hosts by some combination of repeaters, hubs, bridges and switches, but not by network layer routers.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] Examples of physical networks are Ethernet networks and Wi-Fi networks, both of which are IEEE 802 networks and use IEEE 802 48-bit MAC addresses.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] A MAC layer is not required in full-duplex point-to-point communication, but address fields are included in some point-to-point protocols for compatibility reasons.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] The channel access control mechanisms provided by the MAC layer are also known as a multiple access method.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] This makes it possible for several stations connected to the same physical medium to share it.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] Examples of shared physical media are bus networks, ring networks, hub networks, wireless networks and half-duplex point-to-point links.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] The multiple access method may detect or avoid data packet collisions if a packet mode contention based channel access method is used, or reserve resources to establish a logical channel if a circuit-switched or channelization-based channel access method is used.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] The channel access control mechanism relies on a physical layer multiplex scheme.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] The most widespread multiple access method is the contention-based CSMA/CD used in Ethernet networks.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] This mechanism is only utilized within a network collision domain, for example, an Ethernet bus network or a hub-based star topology network.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] An Ethernet network may be divided into several collision domains, interconnected by bridges and switches.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] A multiple access method is not required in a switched full-duplex network, such as today's switched Ethernet networks, but is often available in the equipment for compatibility reasons.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] Use of directional antennas and millimeter-wave communication in a wireless personal area network increases the probability of concurrent scheduling of non‐interfering transmissions in a localized area, which results in an immense increase in network throughput.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] However, the optimum scheduling of concurrent transmission is an NP-hard problem.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] Cellular networks, such as GSM, UMTS or LTE networks, also use a MAC layer.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] The MAC protocol in cellular networks is designed to maximize the utilization of the expensive licensed spectrum.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] The air interface of a cellular network is at layers 1 and 2 of the OSI model; at layer 2, it is divided into multiple protocol layers.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] In UMTS and LTE, those protocols are the Packet Data Convergence Protocol (PDCP), the Radio Link Control (RLC) protocol, and the MAC protocol.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] The base station has absolute control over the air interface and schedules the downlink access as well as the uplink access of all devices.
[src:ethernet/medium-access-control] The MAC protocol is specified by 3GPP in TS 25.321 for UMTS, TS 36.321 for LTE and TS 38.321 for 5G.
